Some parents legally change their child's age at the time of adoption=20
in Kazakhstan.  From what I understand this is "technically"=20
impossible to do in Kaz and Russia -- but I do know of parents who=20
did this during the overseas adoption process -- usually to make=20
their child 1 - 2 years younger.

In other cases, parents either tell their child they are a year=20
younger than they actually are -- and the kids believe this -- while=20
in other cases parents discuss it with the child and agree to=20
consider the child a year or two younger.

Parents in many states also have the option to legally change their=20
child's age at the time of readoption, and sometimes can even=20
petition a judge outside of a readoption.  Standards vary by state=20
and sometimes by jurisdiction as to if/how parents can do this -- so=20
it's best to talk with adoptive families in your community if you are=20
considering legally changing your child's age.  For example, I know=20
parents who simply petitioned the court without any=20
supporting "documentation" as to why the child should be made younger=20
who successfully changed their kids ages -- while other parents had=20
to submit dental, medical and psychological records supporting the=20
position that the child was "younger" than his or her stated age.

>>Yet it will be clear to the child immediately, if not soon, that=20
they are engaged in some sort of deception (no harshness intended),=20
won't it?  Won't they be inclined to want to tell others their "true"=20
